entry.content:
The "default" property on SpeechSynthesisVoice doesn't always

return an expected default voice. e.g. on Linux, a Dutch voice is

default, even though the device and browser language are English.



Still attempt to use the default voice from the list of voices in the

language or all the voices if no voices are found in the default

language.



More work will be done on voice / language management, but this

just enables faster development on Linux with an English voice

for now.

entry.title: Make GetPreviousRenderFrameHostId resilient to current RFH changes
entry.content:
NavigationRequest::GetPreviousRenderFrameHostId() currently returns

the ID of the current RFH at the time the NavigationRequest is

constructed. This means if another RenderFrameHost committed and

replace the current RFH while the navigation is still in progress,

the saved RFH id might become stale.



After auditing [1], all current usage of the function turns out to

want to refer to the latest value of the current RFH up until

the navigation commits and potentially swaps in a new RFH, so this

CL makes it so that the function returns the current RFH if the

navigation hadn't committed a new RFH, and a snapshotted ID of

the current RFH just before the potential swap happens afterwards.



We do still track the original current RFH from request

construction time in current_render_frame_host_id_at_construction_,

but it's currently only needed within NavigationRequest itself, so

it's not exposed outside.



Note: navigation queueing and the early RFH swap are two ways

to change the current RFH in the middle of a navigation.



[1]: https://docs.google.com/document/d/1FSnuLm9vuqjR89v2KD5CcjdAksDs-kZn_XAX4W8yrsU/edit?usp=sharing

entry.title: [zlib] Re-land Introducing ANZAC++ hash
entry.content:
Since 2015 Chromium's zlib used a hardware accelerated hashing function

(i.e. CRC32) to insert symbols in the dictionary during compression.



As it was suggested by Noel Gordon, turns out that a portable hash can

actually outperform it, yielding an average gain of 30% to 40% faster* compression while keeping similar compression ratios**.



In these days, such gains are equivalent to more than 3 generations

of silicon.



The new hashing function is called ANZAC++ and can be technically

considered a multiplicative hash (i.e. multiply-add-shift-mask).



Aside being faster, it is also portable and doesn't depend on crypto

extensions to perform (i.e. will work on RISC-V and Armv7).



This patch will use ANZAC as default hashing, plus performs a huge cleanup.



* Average gains: m1(31.3%), RPL_e(39.7%), RPL_p(39.4%),

Cascade(39%), ICX(+38%), SPR(41.9%).



** Average compression ratio loss is 0.1% for the snappy data

corpus.

fix it ASAP.

entry.title: Fix RFHI::pending_navigate_ cleanup after crashes and early RFH swaps.
entry.content:
When resuming a navigation that had been saved into

RenderFrameHostImpl::pending_navigate_, we need to account for the

fact that OnBeginNavigation() calls GetFrameHostForNavigation() which

may perform an early RenderFrameHost swap and synchronously destroy

the old RFH.



There's also no need to keep a pending_navigate_ around after the

corresponding renderer process crashes, so this CL also adds logic to

clear it. Resuming such a navigation would require additional work,

since the NavigationClient stashed in pending_navigate_ is no longer

usable and would just immediately call the disconnect handler and

cancel the navigation. But there isn't really any benefit to adding

that complexity, and we already cancel the RFH's other ongoing

navigations when its renderer process dies.



This CL also tweaks the logic in RenderWidgetHostImpl to allow the

resuming logic (ResumeLoadingCreatedWebContents) to work without

hitting DCHECKs, if it's called after a renderer process crash. This

case never worked cleanly before, but is supported now (and allows the

new test to work without crashing).

entry.title: [EditContext] Don't set WebTextInputInfo composition ranges if no composition
entry.content:
WebTextInputInfo [1] has a convention where

composition_start/composition_end are set to -1 to indicate there is

no composition. EditContext has a separate bool to track

has_composition_, and keeps composition_range_start_/end_ at 0 when

there is no composition.



EditContext's convention was getting applied to WebTextInputInfo,

erroneously indicating that a composition open when there was not.

This was causing issues with Android touch keyboard suggestions:

when the user chooses a suggested word, the same set of suggestions

are displayed again rather than advancing to the next suggested

word in the sentence.



Fix the issue by leaving WebTextInputInfo.composition_start/

composition_end at -1 if EditContext has no composition.



[1] https://source.chromium.org/chromium/chromium/src/+/main:third_party/blink/public/platform/web_text_input_info.h
